<subSubSection id="C3396559FFA0FF99F3079683FC38BD0E" pageId="5" pageNumber="314" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B9C36D2FFA0FF99F3079683FBFDBEEE" blockId="5.[812,1452,1274,1458]" pageId="5" pageNumber="314">
<emphasis id="B957EAC0FFA0FF99F3079683FC75BE4E" bold="true" box="[813,928,1274,1298]" pageId="5" pageNumber="314">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Small, elongate oval species (body length 
<quantity id="4CDB9B37FFA0FF99F5769683FC8EBE6E" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.6" metricValueMax="3.7" metricValueMin="3.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="314" unit="mm" value="3.6" valueMax="3.7" valueMin="3.5">3.5–3.7 mm</quantity>
). Elytra with subbasal testaceous band very broad, covering at least basal third of elytra; or elytra almost uniformly testaceous (
<figureCitation id="13182A57FFA0FF99F4099723FBB2BE2E" box="[1059,1127,1370,1394]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[113,157,2051,2073]" captionTargetBox="[115,1452,190,2035]" captionTargetId="figure-10@3.[97,1463,180,2039]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 1–9. Habitus of Laccophilus: 1, L. aurofasciatus; 2, L. auropictus; 3, L. ceylonicus; 4, L. elegans; 5, L. girardi; 6, L. hendrichi, new species; 7, L. jaechi, new species; 8, L. javanicus; 9, L. komareki, new species. Scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5385200" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5385200/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="314">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Apical part of median lobe in lateral view almost straight, narrowing to apex which is bent dorsally (
<figureCitation id="13182A57FFA0FF99F3E097E3FBC9BEEE" box="[970,1052,1434,1458]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="7.[113,157,2006,2028]" captionTargetBox="[120,1445,189,1990]" captionTargetId="figure-10@7.[110,1454,186,1997]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs. 18–35. Median lobe in lateral view: 18, Laccophilus aurofasciatus; 19, L. auropictus; 20, L. ceylonicus; 21, L. elegans; 22, L. girardi; 23, L. hendrichi, new species; 24, L. jaechi, new species; 25, L. javanicus; 26, L. kalimantanensis, new species; 27, L. komareki, new species. 28, L. mahakamensis; 29, L. mazzoldii, new species; 30, L. nusatenggaraensis, new species; 31, L. schillhammeri, new species; 32, L. stastnyi, new species; 33, L. tobaensis; 34, L. tonkinensis; 35, L. wittmeri. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5385204" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5385204/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="314">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9C36D2FFA0FF99F30797A3FC38BD0E" blockId="5.[813,1452,1498,1618]" pageId="5" pageNumber="314">
<emphasis id="B957EAC0FFA0FF99F30797A3FC65BEAE" bold="true" box="[813,944,1498,1522]" pageId="5" pageNumber="314">Variability.</emphasis>
A species rather variable in elytral colouration: specimens from Batu Punggul are almost completely testaceous with only indistinct infuscation posteriorly to elytral midlength.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
